                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Hmm, so you're suggesting that a typical pull of a room might be one red, one high blue, one low blue, and two greens? </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Sure, but it doesn't have to be that extreme.  At L 70, blue goes a long way.
<br />

<br />
Take a room with a L 72 mob, L 62 mob and a L 66 mob.  One yellow and 2 blues.
<br />

<br />
800 DPS, 500 DPS and 250 DPS.  35,000 hps, 28,000 hps and 18,000 hps.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">The mobs might have to be linked somehow, to prevent monks from using FD to pull the greens out first, which spoils the whole scheme. Also they'd need to respawn all at once else campers could quickly pull singles as they respawned. In some cases they might need to be uncharmable too (lest a dire charm prevent them from ever respawning at all).</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
